7. What is the function of mast cells?
That’s right! Sensitized mast cells release mediators of inflammation (histamine, chemotactic factors) upon encountering antigen.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Activated mast cells immediately release:
histamine, which causes:
vasodilatation; increases blood flow 
increased vascular permeability; (esp. post-capillary venules) increases production of protein-rich tissue fluid (edema) and slows blood flow.
neutrophil chemotactic factor: attracts neutrophils
eosinophil chemotactic factor: attracts eosinophils

Mast cells store chemical mediators of inflammation and hypersensitivity reactions
activated by trauma or by presence of antigen
become sensitized to a specific antigen when antibodies made against that antigen become bound to receptors on the mast cell membranes
